 of current issues in media ethics, this book challenges students to explore the relationship between media ethics and social change. It considers the potentially beneficial uses of media practice for humanity, addressing questions of inclusivity and diversity and specialist topics that are absent from other texts. Using case studies and exercises based on real-life experiences of journalists, newsmakers, policy makers and consumers, Valerie Alia invites readers to examine current media practice and develop strategies for ethical problem solving and decision-making.Topics discussed include: ethical theories; social scientific theories; the search for a responsible practice; internationalisation of the media; the ethics of interviewing; politicians, power and spin; media, minorities and gender; arts, sports and travel; ethics and images; changing technologies; and codes and principles.FeaturesThe only book to consider media ethics in the context of social changeProvides current examples of British and international media practice, theory, problem-solving exercises, workshop simulations and case studiesIncludes original cartoons, rare photographs of great 'muckrakers', an annotated list of relevant films, and a full bibliography and index.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMass mediaxMoral and ethical aspects. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147446389840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474463898423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474463898/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA